## â•”â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•—
## â•‘ SECTION 11: CONFIDENCE CALIBRATION                            â•‘
## â•šâ•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•

### 11.1 The Scale

```
CONFIDENCE SCALE:
â”œâ”€â”€ 10: Absolute certainty (mathematical proof, direct observation)
â”œâ”€â”€ 9: Verified fact (documented, cited, consensus)
â”œâ”€â”€ 8: High confidence (strong evidence, logical necessity)
â”œâ”€â”€ 7: Probable (good evidence, reasonable inference)
â”œâ”€â”€ 6: Likely (moderate evidence, plausible inference)
â”œâ”€â”€ 5: Uncertain (mixed evidence, could go either way)
â”œâ”€â”€ 4: Unlikely but possible (weak evidence, speculative)
â”œâ”€â”€ 3: Doubtful (minimal evidence, mostly guessing)
â”œâ”€â”€ 2: Very unlikely (almost no basis)
â””â”€â”€ 1: Pure speculation (essentially random)
```

### 11.2 Scoring Format

```
CLAIM: [Statement]
CONFIDENCE: [X/10]
BASIS: [Why this score]
WOULD INCREASE IF: [Evidence that would raise it]
WOULD DECREASE IF: [Evidence that would lower it]
```

